==English==

===Etymology===
* (As verb). Possibly meaning to pack tightly, as in [[kernel]]s on an ear of maize.

===Noun===

'''kern'''

# A light-armed foot soldier of the ancient militia of Ireland and Scotland;  often used as a term of contempt.
#:'''Quotation'''
#:* '''c.1599''': "O, then belike she was old and gentle; and you rode like a '''kern''' of Ireland, your French hose off and in your strait strossers." &mdash; ''Henry V: Ac.3 Sc7,'' Wm. Shakespeare.
# In [[hot-metal]] printing, a '''kern''' is any part of a letter which extends into the space used by another letter.

===Transitive verb===
'''kern''' ('''kerning''', '''kerned''', '''kerned''')

# To adjust the horizontal space between selected pairs of letters (characters or [[glyph]]s), particularly in a [[proportional]] [[font]] (printing).

===Intransitive verb===
'''kern''' ('''kerning''', '''kerned''', '''kerned''')

# To perform a [[kerning]] adjustment.